No Duplication
Dictionaries do not allow duplicate keys! If we use the same key twice, only the last key will remain.

person = {
    "name": "John",
    "name": "Smith",
    "age": 25,
    "city": "New York"
}

print(person)

{'name': 'Smith', 'age': 25, 'city': 'New York'}


However we can have duplicate values:

person = {
    "name": "John",
    "age": 25,
    "city": "John"
}

print(person)

{'name': 'John', 'age': 25, 'city': 'John'}

The else Statement
The else statement works in conjunction with if. It allows us to provide an alternative code block to execute if the if condition is not met. Here’s how it looks:
if &lt;condition&gt;:
    &lt;code to run if the condition is True&gt;
else:
    &lt;code to run if the condition is False&gt;
Once again, be very mindful of the indentation:
&lt;we always run this&gt;

if &lt;condition&gt;:
    &lt;code to run if the condition is True&gt;
else:
    &lt;code to run if the condition is False&gt;

&lt;we always run this&gt;

# This code checks if a student passed an exam
# Assuming a mark 0-10

grade = 7

if grade &gt;= 5:
  print("You passed")
else:
  print("You have not passed")

You passed


